traight Talk Express” while researching for the original article published in the April 2000 issue of ","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":288,"offset":1406},"end":{"line":15,"column":568,"offset":1686}}},{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Rolling Stone.","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":569,"offset":1687},"end":{"line":15,"column":583,"offset":1701}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":568,"offset":1686},"end":{"line":15,"column":584,"offset":1702}}},{"type":"text","value":" This year maverick McCain made a lot of headlines//received a lot of press coverage standing up to the Trump agenda and because of his brain cancer diagnosis (and also due to the latter while also conducting the former). “Up Simba” gives an amazingly detailed account of McCain’s time spend as a prisoner of war during the Vietnam War (another topic that was made highly relevant in 2017 with the release of Ken Burns ","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":584,"offset":1702},"end":{"line":15,"column":1003,"offset":2121}}},{"type":"text","value":"&","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1003,"offset":2121},"end":{"line":15,"column":1008,"offset":2126}}},{"type":"text","value":" Lynn Novick’s incredible PBS documentary film on the topic).","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1008,"offset":2126},"end":{"line":15,"column":1069,"offset":2187}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1,"offset":1119},"end":{"line":15,"column":1069,"offset":2187}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4682/24572668507_b93690b831.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1,"offset":2189},"end":{"line":17,"column":68,"offset":2256}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1,"offset":2189},"end":{"line":17,"column":68,"offset":2256}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"3. The Master and Margarita by Mikhail Bulgakov","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":3,"offset":2260},"end":{"line":19,"column":50,"offset":2307}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1,"offset":2258},"end":{"line":19,"column":52,"offset":2309}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1,"offset":2258},"end":{"line":19,"column":52,"offset":2309}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Another novel incorporating the talking cat motif. I would be lying if the talking black cat wasn’t at least partially a pull here for me. This one is a classic and I’m trying to slowly catch up on my Russian literature (I think one novel from the genre/year is sufficient because they’re always such downers). The novel combines two parts–one set in ancient Jerusalem (a city that has personal relevance for me this year and that’s received even more global attention than usual as of late) and one in contemporary Moscow. The devil visits Moscow (an atheist state, under Stalin’s rule) with a vodka and chess-loving black cat, while the plot of Pontius Pilate plays out in what later emerges as a novel (written by a writer, known as the Master). The Master’s mistress, Margarita is tempted by the devil. This one is a surreal dark comedy that will force your mind though existential hoops.","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1,"offset":2311},"end":{"line":21,"column":893,"offset":3203}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1,"offset":2311},"end":{"line":21,"column":893,"offset":3203}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4679/38730924994_2bd05eebc3.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1,"offset":3205},"end":{"line":23,"column":68,"offset":3272}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1,"offset":3205},"end":{"line":23,"column":68,"offset":3272}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"4. Things Fall Apart by Chinua Achebe","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":3,"offset":3276},"end":{"line":25,"column":40,"offset":3313}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1,"offset":3274},"end":{"line":25,"column":42,"offset":3315}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1,"offset":3274},"end":{"line":25,"column":42,"offset":3315}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This one is a post-colonial classic (that also ventures into pre-colonial life) in late nineteenth century Nigeria. I never had to read it in school (like many did), but I enjoyed it in adulthood–from the descriptions of patriarchal tribal native customs to the heavy blows of British colonialism and Christian missionaries on one man’s (Okonkwo) life and on the Igbo community.","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1,"offset":3317},"end":{"line":27,"column":379,"offset":3695}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1,"offset":3317},"end":{"line":27,"column":379,"offset":3695}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4593/38730924774_aa5903ba6b.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1,"offset":3697},"end":{"line":29,"column":68,"offset":3764}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1,"offset":3697},"end":{"line":29,"column":68,"offset":3764}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"5. Strangers in Their Own Land by Arlie Russell Hochschild","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":3,"offset":3768},"end":{"line":31,"column":61,"offset":3826}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1,"offset":3766},"end":{"line":31,"column":63,"offset":3828}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1,"offset":3766},"end":{"line":31,"column":63,"offset":3828}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This book recommendation from a close friend was the perfect dovetail from J.D. Vance’s ","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1,"offset":3830},"end":{"line":33,"column":89,"offset":3918}}},{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Hillbilly Elegy.","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":90,"offset":3919},"end":{"line":33,"column":106,"offset":3935}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":89,"offset":3918},"end":{"line":33,"column":107,"offset":3936}}},{"type":"text","value":" After scrambling to answer ‘How did ","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":107,"offset":3936},"end":{"line":33,"column":144,"offset":3973}}},{"type":"text","value":"[","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":144,"offset":3973},"end":{"line":33,"column":146,"offset":3975}}},{"type":"text","value":"Trump’s election","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":146,"offset":3975},"end":{"line":33,"column":162,"offset":3991}}},{"type":"text","value":"]","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":162,"offset":3991},"end":{"line":33,"column":164,"offset":3993}}},{"type":"text","value":" happen?’ in late 2016 into early 2017, we ","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":164,"offset":3993},"end":{"line":33,"column":207,"offset":4036}}},{"type":"text","value":"[","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":207,"offset":4036},"end":{"line":33,"column":209,"offset":4038}}},{"type":"text","value":"woke folks in America","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":209,"offset":4038},"end":{"line":33,"column":230,"offset":4059}}},{"type":"text","value":"]","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":230,"offset":4059},"end":{"line":33,"column":232,"offset":4061}}},{"type":"text","value":" found ourselves voraciously reading anything we could get our hands on to explain this all away. Hochschild is a Berkley sociologist (it’s not as bad as it may sound) interested in how people on the right think. She spent five years in Louisiana talking with people on the other side of her “empathy wall.” (Defined as an obstacle that prevents a deep understanding with another person). She picked the state because it ranks 49th in ‘human development’ and extremely low in overall heath, education and child well-being, yet its citizens mostly spurn federal help. Despite the environmental concerns that local industry poses, they are also extremely anti-government regulation. The simplified logic behind it all is more oil = more jobs = more prosperity and less need for government. It’s a fascinating look at a small pocket of America until a microscope–in a slightly different vein from Vance’s story.","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":232,"offset":4061},"end":{"line":33,"column":1140,"offset":4969}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1,"offset":3830},"end":{"line":33,"column":1140,"offset":4969}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4599/24572670117_af4d4329fc.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1,"offset":4971},"end":{"line":35,"column":68,"offset":5038}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1,"offset":4971},"end":{"line":35,"column":68,"offset":5038}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"6. Beautiful Ruins by Jess Walter","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":3,"offset":5042},"end":{"line":37,"column":36,"offset":5075}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1,"offset":5040},"end":{"line":37,"column":38,"offset":5077}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1,"offset":5040},"end":{"line":37,"column":38,"offset":5077}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A friend of a friend I met at a party recommended this one when I mentioned that I loved the Elena Ferrante novels. It’s not fair to call it a trashy beach read, because it warrants more praise and merit than that, but I would group it in the same category as the Ferrante books. It’s a love story at its core, taking place in the 1960s on the coast of the Ligurian Sea. An Italian innkeeper meets an American actress and what ensues is a story outlined over the course of fifty years. It’s hopeful and gripping.","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1,"offset":5079},"end":{"line":39,"column":513,"offset":5591}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1,"offset":5079},"end":{"line":39,"column":513,"offset":5591}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4736/38730926454_31456e1057.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1,"offset":5593},"end":{"line":41,"column":68,"offset":5660}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1,"offset":5593},"end":{"line":41,"column":68,"offset":5660}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"7. Acid Test by Tom Shroder","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":3,"offset":5664},"end":{"line":43,"column":30,"offset":5691}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1,"offset":5662},"end":{"line":43,"column":32,"offset":5693}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1,"offset":5662},"end":{"line":43,"column":32,"offset":5693}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I found this book on a ‘leave a book, take a book’ shelf in a Moroccan hotel in the fall of 2016. The subject matter piqued my interest and though the narratives were a bit hard to follow at times, it does a good job outlining successful case studies where individuals with PTSD used controlled amounts of psychedelic drugs to help their psyche. Overly regulated and wildly cast as illegal and dangerous, these drugs have true healing properties.","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1,"offset":5695},"end":{"line":45,"column":447,"offset":6141}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1,"offset":5695},"end":{"line":45,"column":447,"offset":6141}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4682/38730926714_73b0d53134.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1,"offset":6143},"end":{"line":47,"column":68,"offset":6210}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1,"offset":6143},"end":{"line":47,"column":68,"offset":6210}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"8. Steve Jobs by Walter Isaacson","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":3,"offset":6214},"end":{"line":49,"column":35,"offset":6246}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1,"offset":6212},"end":{"line":49,"column":37,"offset":6248}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1,"offset":6212},"end":{"line":49,"column":37,"offset":6248}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I attended a commencement speech in May where Walter Isaacson was the keynote. It was a really wonderful speech and Isaacson quoted job a lot–because he spent so much time with him after Jobs persistently requested that Isaacson be his personal biographer after Jobs knew his cancer case was terminal. Isaacson is an incredible biographer and he interviewed over 100 of those close to Jobs for this book. He also made a point to seek out all angles of the story–he interviewed his loved ones as well as people who Jobs screwed over in business. The book also outlines (in great detail) the entire trajectory of Apple, from an idea Jobs had with Steve Wozniak (“Woz”) to Steve breaking off to form NeXT, to ripping off Xerox’s technology to present day. Jobs insisted that the masses were too stupid to know what they wanted and had to be told (he was against market research and what’s today known as user experience design), but still ultimately knew exactly to deliver a product that would succeed. He was heavily influenced by the Bauhaus and insisted on rounded corners. He was also vehemently against the stylus and it’s my personal opinion that he’s rolling in his grave over the Apple pencil. This was definitely my top read of the year and Jobs’ complicated backstory and fascinating mind are described so well in this work.","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1,"offset":6250},"end":{"line":51,"column":1333,"offset":7582}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1,"offset":6250},"end":{"line":51,"column":1333,"offset":7582}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4727/38730926774_90f01f8f7b.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1,"offset":7584},"end":{"line":53,"column":68,"offset":7651}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1,"offset":7584},"end":{"line":53,"column":68,"offset":7651}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"9. Swing Time by Zadie Smith","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":3,"offset":7655},"end":{"line":55,"column":31,"offset":7683}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1,"offset":7653},"end":{"line":55,"column":33,"offset":7685}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1,"offset":7653},"end":{"line":55,"column":33,"offset":7685}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This was my first Zadie Smith book, and perhaps I should have started elsewhere. The story jumps between London and West Africa, and switches between the past and present to tell the story of friendship between two brown girls, and their respective hardships through the lens of competitive dance. The plot was lacking, but again sort of reminiscent of the Ferrante novels in the way that they outline the antagonistic aspect of female friendship and coming of age. Despite this experience I still want to read ","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1,"offset":7687},"end":{"line":57,"column":512,"offset":8198}}},{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"White Teeth","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":513,"offset":8199},"end":{"line":57,"column":524,"offset":8210}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":512,"offset":8198},"end":{"line":57,"column":525,"offset":8211}}},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":525,"offset":8211},"end":{"line":57,"column":526,"offset":8212}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1,"offset":7687},"end":{"line":57,"column":526,"offset":8212}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4739/24572670407_c3233b0135.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1,"offset":8214},"end":{"line":59,"column":68,"offset":8281}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1,"offset":8214},"end":{"line":59,"column":68,"offset":8281}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"10. The Inner Sky by Steven Forrest","position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":3,"offset":8285},"end":{"line":61,"column":38,"offset":8320}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1,"offset":8283},"end":{"line":61,"column":40,"offset":8322}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1,"offset":8283},"end":{"line":61,"column":40,"offset":8322}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I did a bit of research into what a good first read on astrology would be, since I wanted to learn a bit more about signs and such. This was a pretty good introduction covering the planet, the signs, houses, and aspects. It also includes a chapter on how to interpret charts. I’ll need to follow it up with something that goes more in-depth, since there are still a lot of gaps in my knowledge.","position":{"start":{"line":63,"column":1,"offset":8324},"end":{"line":63,"column":395,"offset":8718}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":63,"column":1,"offset":8324},"end":{"line":63,"column":395,"offset":8718}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4734/24572670277_e0d8bcf8e9.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1,"offset":8720},"end":{"line":65,"column":68,"offset":8787}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1,"offset":8720},"end":{"line":65,"column":68,"offset":8787}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","v